<br>
So, technically as I read it, using a piece of software to alter the behavior of EQ that came from the OS maker is a 'third party' program.<br>
<br>
Of course, this gets all very fuzzy very fast. Did Sony agree (click-wrap or by signature) that by writing their program, it would not usurp Window's ability to multitask? Is this an understood rule? Where does Microsoft dictate this? If it's in Microsoft's EULA, that doesn't exactally apply to software makers so much as it does the end user (which doesn't make sense, unless they're trying to keep the End User from developing software to break Window's Multitasking)? Is it an upholdable contract if there was no direct acknowledgement by Sony that such a break in the Multitasking feature was against Microsoft's design policy?<br>
<br>
And on and on :P Kinda funny, but there's got to be more to this. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=runemaker>RuneMaker</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Arch Mage</span><br>  Posts: 399<br> <font color=#333333>(11/4/02 6:54:26 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7714.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Third party software</span><hr size=1> <br>
