<br>
Win98-Xp is listed in the requirements section, but they don't make any claims about being 'Designed for Windows X'.  <br>
<br>
I'm of the opinion that anyone can write any program they want for windows, as long as they are clear about what their program does. <br>
<br>
I know MS has a certification process to obtain the &quot;designed for&quot; logo, but I'm not sure if their rights extend too far beyond the use of that logo....<br>
<br>
SOE should consider splitting their legal documents and making them more readable. 1) EULA which applies to the EQGame.exe application 2) A terms of service agreement which applies to the monthly fee we pay to access their servers, and what kind of activities are to be allowed on your system while you are accessing their servers. I think splitting the document might help people understand things a little bit better.<br>
<br>
Technically, if you get busted running programs like EQ Windows or ShowEQ, SOE doesn't take away your ability to run their program, they simply deny you access to their servers, which, since it is a service, is a completely different matter than software licensing.<br>
