<br>
The &quot;Windows Logo&quot; program is a set of qualifications that, if met, enables a software designer to use special logos and seals in their advertising and marketing.  <br>
<br>
For example, if I design a word processor, and wish to use the Windows logo on my box as a &quot;guarantee&quot; to my customers that I am compatible with whatever version of Windows I'm programming for, I can meet certain specs set forth by Microsoft in order to get certified by them.<br>
<br>
Once certified, I can slap their logo (the ones they specify) on my box.  Customers feel a little more secure, and off we go.<br>
<br>
Most programs, btw, don't bother.  The logo specs are a pain in the butt.<br>
